<DocsLayout title="HUMANFILE" description="The operator identity document. Tells the OS who you are, what models to use, what secrets are authorized, and how to calibrate.">
    <p>Your compiled identity. The OS reads this at boot and calibrates to you.</p>

    <h2>What it is</h2>
    <p>
      HUMANFILE is the document that tells the OS who you are, what models and secrets
      agents can use, what drivers to load, and how to preprocess input. Not a config file &mdash; a governance document.
      You write it once. Every agent that runs under your OS reads it.
    </p>
    <p>Location: <code>.ostk/HUMANFILE</code> (project-level) or <code>~/.HUMANFILE</code> (global, shared across all projects).</p>

    <h2>Example</h2>
    <pre><code># HUMANFILE &mdash; @scott

IDENTITY scott
SIGN 7141A45868F8295E5BEB6286BAF08C963C7E3184

MODEL claude-opus-4-6
FALLBACK mistral-large-latest

AVAILABLE &lt;&lt;MODELS
claude-sonnet-4-5
claude-opus-4-6
claude-haiku-4-5
gemini-2.5-pro
gemini-3.1-pro
mistral-large-latest
codestral-latest
MODELS

SECRET &lt;&lt;KEYS
ANTHROPIC_API_KEY
GEMINI_API_KEY
OPENROUTER_API_KEY
MISTRAL_API_KEY
KEYS

DRIVER rust fcp-rust

EMBED codebase

PREPROCESS apple/default</code></pre>

    <h2>Directives</h2>
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr><th>Directive</th><th>Required</th><th>Description</th></tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td><code>IDENTITY</code></td><td>Yes</td><td>Your username. Used in audit attribution and agent identity.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>SIGN</code></td><td>No</td><td>GPG key fingerprint. Establishes T0 trust tier when verified.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>MODEL</code></td><td>Yes</td><td>Default model for agent sessions. The kernel auto-detects provider from model name.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>FALLBACK</code></td><td>No</td><td>Model to use when the primary is unavailable or rate-limited.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>AVAILABLE &lt;&lt;MODELS</code></td><td>No</td><td>Heredoc block listing all models the OS is authorized to use. Consumed by <code>FROM auto</code> in Agentfiles.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>SECRET &lt;&lt;KEYS</code></td><td>No</td><td>Heredoc block listing authorized API key names. Keys are stored in the platform keychain &mdash; never in the file itself.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>DRIVER &lt;type&gt; &lt;name&gt;</code></td><td>No</td><td>FCP driver to load at boot. <code>type</code> is the driver kind (e.g. <code>rust</code>), <code>name</code> is the binary name (e.g. <code>fcp-rust</code>). Internal drivers (fcp-screen, fcp-web) don't need a declaration.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>EMBED</code></td><td>No</td><td>Embedding index mode. <code>codebase</code> = full index at boot. <code>incremental</code> = git-diff-only updates. <code>off</code> = disable.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>PREPROCESS</code></td><td>No</td><td>Local model for preprocessing user input (grammar correction, intent expansion). Values: <code>apple/default</code> (on-device), or a model path.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>TRUST</code></td><td>No</td><td>Trust policy for Agentfile signing. <code>unsigned</code> skips the signature requirement for agent dispatch.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>EXTENDS</code></td><td>No</td><td>Path to a parent HUMANFILE for inheritance. Project-level HUMANFILE can extend a global one. Child directives override parent.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>BOOT</code></td><td>No</td><td>Custom boot steps appended after the kernel's initialization sequence. e.g. <code>BOOT :verify-codeowners</code></td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>VERB</code></td><td>No</td><td>Custom verb registration merged into <code>.language</code> at boot. Extends the syscall table without editing the language file directly.</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <h2>Secrets</h2>
    <p>
      The <code>SECRET</code> block is the only place where API keys are authorized for agent use.
      If a key isn't listed, agents cannot access it &mdash; even if it exists in your system keychain.
    </p>
    <p>The kernel resolves secrets in order:</p>
    <ol>
      <li><strong>BYO secret manager</strong> &mdash; set <code>OSTK_SECRET_CMD</code> to your tool (<code>bw</code>, <code>op</code>, <code>pass</code>). See <a href="/docs/env-vars">Environment Variables</a>.</li>
      <li><strong>Platform keychain</strong> &mdash; <code>ostk secret set KEY</code> stores in macOS Keychain / Linux secret-tool</li>
      <li><strong>Environment variable</strong> &mdash; fallback to <code>$KEY</code> in your shell env</li>
    </ol>
    <p>Provider mapping:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><code>claude-*</code> &rarr; <code>ANTHROPIC_API_KEY</code></li>
      <li><code>gemini-*</code> &rarr; <code>GEMINI_API_KEY</code></li>
      <li><code>mistral-*</code> / <code>codestral-*</code> &rarr; <code>MISTRAL_API_KEY</code></li>
      <li><code>openrouter/*</code> &rarr; <code>OPENROUTER_API_KEY</code></li>
    </ul>

    <h2>GPG signing</h2>
    <p>
      Signing your HUMANFILE establishes T0 operator identity &mdash; the highest trust tier.
      Without a signature, the OS operates at T2 (named, unverified).
    </p>
    <pre><code>ostk sign</code></pre>
    <p>This signs the HUMANFILE with the GPG key specified in your <code>SIGN</code> directive. The signature file (<code>HUMANFILE.asc</code>) is read at boot alongside HUMANFILE.</p>

    <h2>Inheritance</h2>
    <p><code>~/.HUMANFILE</code> applies to all projects on your machine. <code>.ostk/HUMANFILE</code> is project-specific and takes precedence. Use <code>EXTENDS</code> to inherit from a parent:</p>
    <pre><code># .ostk/HUMANFILE
EXTENDS ~/.HUMANFILE

# Override just the model for this project
MODEL claude-haiku-4-5</code></pre>
    <p>Child directives override parent. Secrets, models, and drivers merge (child adds to parent's list). The global file is created by <code>ostk init --guided</code>.</p>

